In [[climate science]], a '''biosphere model''', is used to [[climate modelling|model]] the [[biosphere]] of Earth, and can be coupled with atmospheric [[Global climate model|general circulation models]] (GCMs) for modelling the entire [[climate system]].

== Models ==
The [[Daisyworld]] computer simulation from 1983, calculated how [[Earth's radiation balance|radiant energy]] increased or decreased, dependent on the [[albedo]] effect, based on changes in the biosphere.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Wood |first=Andrew J. |author2=G.J. Ackland |author3=J.G. Dyke |author4=H.T.P. Williams |author5=T.M. Lenton |title=Daisyworld: A review |journal=[[Reviews of Geophysics]] |volume=48 |issue=RG1001 |publisher=[[American Geophysical Union]] |date=2008-01-05   |url=http://www.agu.org/pubs/crossref/2008/2006RG000217.shtml |doi=10.1029/2006RG000217  |pages=RG1001|bibcode = 2008RvGeo..46.1001W }}</ref>

The Simple Biosphere (SiB) model, presented by Sellers et al. in 1986, calculates transfer of energy, mass and momentum of the atmosphere and the vegetated surface of the Earth. The model is designed for use in atmospheric ''general circulation models'', to account for the related climate attribution of the biosphere.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sellers|year=1986|title=A simple biosphere model (SiB) for use within general circulation models|journal=Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences|issue=43|pages=505–531|doi=10.1175/1520-0469(1986)043<0505:ASBMFU>2.0.CO;2|volume=43|url=http://journals.ametsoc.org/doi/abs/10.1175/1520-0469(1986)043%3C0505%3AASBMFU%3E2.0.CO%3B2|display-authors=etal}}</ref> A revised version was published in 1996 and incorporates satellite measurements.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sellers|year=1996|title=A Revised Land Surface Parameterization (SiB2) for Atmospheric GCMS. Part II: The Generation of Global Fields of Terrestrial Biophysical Parameters from Satellite Data|journal=Journal of Climate|pages=707–737|doi=10.1175/1520-0469(1986)043<0505:ASBMFU>2.0.CO;2|volume=9|url=http://journals.ametsoc.org/doi/abs/10.1175/1520-0442(1996)009%3C0706%3AARLSPF%3E2.0.CO%3B2|display-authors=etal}}</ref>

The Ent Dynamic Terrestrial Biosphere Model is a global vegetation model for use with the [[Earth System Modeling Framework]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ent Dynamic Terrestrial Biosphere Model|url=https://www.giss.nasa.gov/projects/ent/|website=Goddard Institute for Space Physics|publisher=NASA|accessdate=27 August 2017|language=en}}</ref>

